00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:07.430
TAMMY STERN: Mitchel
Resnick is a Professor

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:11.930
of Learning Research at the MIT
Media Lab, where he develops

00:00:11.930 --> 00:00:14.270
new technologies and
activities to engage

00:00:14.270 --> 00:00:19.220
people, especially children, in
creative learning experiences.

00:00:19.220 --> 00:00:22.700
His research team, called the
Lifelong Kindergarten Group,

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:26.540
develops the Scratch programming
software and online community,

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:29.780
the world's largest
coding platform for kids.

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:32.830
His group also collaborates
with the LEGO company

00:00:32.830 --> 00:00:35.240
on the development of
new educational ideas

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:40.160
and products, including LEGO
MINDSTORMS robotics kits.

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:42.980
Mitchel co-founded the
Computer Clubhouse Project,

00:00:42.980 --> 00:00:46.640
an international network of
100 after school centers,

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:48.830
where youth from low
income communities

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:51.050
learn to express
themselves creatively

00:00:51.050 --> 00:00:53.790
with new technologies.

00:00:53.790 --> 00:00:55.170
Mitchel and the
Scratch team have

00:00:55.170 --> 00:00:57.330
partnered with
Google and Google.org

00:00:57.330 --> 00:01:01.260
to increase youth coding efforts
through projects like CS First,

00:01:01.260 --> 00:01:04.530
Google's CS curriculum
for nine to 14-year-olds,

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:08.940
and Blockly, which makes the
app development more accessible.

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:12.450
On a personal note, I worked
with Mitchel to develop Scratch

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:15.180
and traveled around the
world doing Scratch workshops

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:17.930
with children and educators.

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:21.440
I remember how exciting it was
for kids to build projects,

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:23.600
bringing their
creations to life,

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:25.940
and how enabling and
empowering these tools

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:28.310
can be for those who
might not otherwise

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:30.970
have found themselves coding.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:32.980
Working with Mitchel
and the Scratch team

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.710
helped me internalize
that coding did not

00:01:35.710 --> 00:01:39.550
need to be an exclusive skill
restricted to engineers,

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:42.580
but rather a tool to
enable anyone to creatively

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:47.350
express themselves, or to tackle
personally meaningful projects.

00:01:47.350 --> 00:01:50.560
Mitchel's passion for people,
education, and empowerment

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:53.170
has inspired me and
countless others,

00:01:53.170 --> 00:01:57.250
and I'm excited to introduce
him to speak with you all today.

