00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:47.950
So I want to start
with a story of one

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:49.970
of those millions
of young people,

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:52.330
just to give a sense of
what the experience is

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:56.314
like for young people when they
join this Scratch community.

00:03:56.314 --> 00:03:58.480
So this is the story about
a young person-- everyone

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:00.190
starts with a user name.

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:03.130
This is someone whose
username was Ipzy.

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:06.280
And Ipzy described-- you know,
when Ipzy was growing up,

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:08.870
one of their favorite
things to do was drawing.

00:04:08.870 --> 00:04:10.090
They loved to draw things.

00:04:10.090 --> 00:04:12.040
And Ipzy got
started with Scratch

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.830
when one of Ipzy's
friends explained

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:17.930
that Scratch was a way to
make her drawings come alive.

00:04:17.930 --> 00:04:19.860
And that was really
intriguing for Ipzy.

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:21.760
So Ipzy tried out, Scratch.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.830
And this is one of
the first projects

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:25.842
that they worked on in Scratch.

00:04:25.842 --> 00:04:27.550
And what I like about
this is you can see

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:30.280
it's Ipzy's drawing, and there's
just a little bit of animation.

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:33.810
You see the ears are wiggling
and the eyes are moving.

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:37.060
And you can almost see here
Ipzy starting with something

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:39.280
that they're comfortable
with, and like dipping

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:41.230
their toe in the water
to try something new.

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:43.217
So this is the
Scratch programming.

00:04:43.217 --> 00:04:45.050
For those who haven't
seen it, with Scratch,

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:46.810
you build up programs
by stacking together

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:48.760
graphical programming blocks.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:52.150
This is one of Ipzy's
first programs and project,

00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:55.450
as a way to start exploring
to testing something new.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:57.460
And Ipzy found that
they really enjoyed

00:04:57.460 --> 00:04:59.080
working on these
types of projects,

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:01.750
so they started spending
more time on Scratch.

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:04.330
A little while later,
this is a project

00:05:04.330 --> 00:05:06.310
that really got Ipzy
known in the community.

00:05:06.310 --> 00:05:09.890
You can see Ipzy's projects got
more and more sophisticated.

00:05:09.890 --> 00:05:13.110
This is a project that Ipzy
worked on called Lemonade Time.

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.790
And in this project, you
can use the arrow keys

00:05:15.790 --> 00:05:17.230
to move the otter.

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:18.970
And as the otter moves
around, the otter

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:22.150
gets tips from different
animals that the otter comes

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.800
across-- the bird, the frog.

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:26.770
And the goal is to be able to
get all the ingredients to make

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:27.400
lemonade.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:28.975
So you have to
get the ideas, you

00:05:28.975 --> 00:05:31.630
have get instructions
and tips, on where

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:35.320
to get the water, the lemons,
the sugar to make lemonade.

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:37.390
So Ipzy put this in
the online community

00:05:37.390 --> 00:05:38.909
and it became really popular.

00:05:38.909 --> 00:05:40.450
So if you go to the
online community,

00:05:40.450 --> 00:05:41.455
you can still see this.

00:05:41.455 --> 00:05:43.810
This is the page
for Lemonade Time.

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:47.140
And you can see it was
viewed 17,000 times.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:50.320
It was loved close
to 2,000 times.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.480
It was remixed 88 times.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:55.700
Because in Scratch,
anybody can take a project

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:58.780
and then make modifications
to it, changing the images,

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:00.110
changing the code.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:02.680
It's all sort of an open
source culture around Scratch.

00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:05.164
Everything that is shared is
covered by Creative Commons.

00:06:05.164 --> 00:06:06.580
So as long as you
give credit, you

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:08.600
can remix other
people's projects.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:12.310
So 88 people made remixed
projects of Lemonade Time.

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:15.130
Nearly 2,000 people--
1,830 people--

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:17.200
gave comments,
giving suggestions

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:19.120
or feedback or encouragement.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:21.871
And you can tell that Ipzy was
listening to these comments

00:06:21.871 --> 00:06:23.620
and reading them
carefully, because if you

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:26.260
look in the instructions
here, it says, "edit--

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:30.260
due to popular demand, the otter
walks a little faster now."

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:32.080
So like any good
designer, Ipzy's

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:34.250
listening to the audience
and making changes,

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:36.430
based on what comes across.

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:39.310
A lot of the comments
we're about Ipzy's artwork.

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:40.810
People really liked
Ipzy's artwork.

00:06:40.810 --> 00:06:42.374
And several people
said, we'd love

00:06:42.374 --> 00:06:43.540
to see more of your artwork.

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:45.830
Can you share more
of your artwork?

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:50.790
So Ipzy started putting up some
projects like this one, branded

00:06:50.790 --> 00:06:52.870
as Ipzy Studio.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:56.610
And it's a collection
of different artwork

00:06:56.610 --> 00:06:59.020
that Ipzy's sharing with
the rest the community.

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:01.440
And Ipzy wrote, "You can edit
them as much as you want,

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:04.100
but you must credit me if you
use any of these sprites."

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:06.580
Sprites are the
objects in Scratch.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:08.370
And this is a sign
that Ipzy was learning

00:07:08.370 --> 00:07:10.680
how to be a good member
of the online community,

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:13.530
and sort of understanding
this idea of sharing

00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:14.554
under Creative Commons.

00:07:14.554 --> 00:07:16.470
And this was definitely
an evolution for Ipzy,

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:18.570
as it is for many
members of the community.

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:21.090
At first, Ipzy was
upset when people

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:24.510
were taking their projects and
remixing them or using them

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:26.570
in different ways, or
taking characters, feeling

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:29.140
like, that's my character, they
shouldn't be able to do it.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:31.245
But over time, Ipzy
came to recognize that,

00:07:31.245 --> 00:07:33.690
when everyone shares,
everyone benefits.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:36.810
At this end, our team, we
were in constant communication

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:38.310
with people in the
community, trying

00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:39.601
to help people understand this.

00:07:39.601 --> 00:07:40.942
But it's a constant--

00:07:40.942 --> 00:07:42.900
sometimes, we always say,
learning how to share

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:45.095
is even more difficult
than learning how to code.

00:07:45.095 --> 00:07:47.220
So that's the real thing
that I think a lot of kids

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:48.420
are learning.

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:50.070
But you know, Ipzy
was doing this,

00:07:50.070 --> 00:07:51.730
but then, as they
continued to do it,

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:53.730
they came up with all
sorts of different things.

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:56.010
Here was even a
tutorial that Ipzy

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:58.410
did showing how to make
scrolling backgrounds.

00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:01.470
You saw in the Lemonade
Time, that the background

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:03.720
was scrolling behind
the otter character,

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:05.040
as you moved the otter.

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:07.060
It's not so easy to make
scrolling backgrounds

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:07.980
in Scratch.

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:09.460
We're trying to figure
out how to make it easier,

00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:10.470
but it's not so easy.

00:08:10.470 --> 00:08:12.510
But Ipzy figured
out how to do it,

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:15.390
and they made this tutorial
showing how to do it,

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:18.475
and then even commented the code
showing people how to do it.

00:08:18.475 --> 00:08:21.390
This, again, suddenly
took us by surprise.

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:24.330
When we imagined that
we would do tutorials,

00:08:24.330 --> 00:08:26.420
and some teachers
would do tutorials,

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:28.770
what took us by surprise
is that so many kids

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:29.990
wanted to do tutorials.

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:31.490
So if you go to the
Scratch website,

00:08:31.490 --> 00:08:32.880
there are thousands
and thousands

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:35.980
of tutorials done by
kids-- how to do scrolling,

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:38.659
you know, how to use variables,
how to use the vector paint

00:08:38.659 --> 00:08:41.400
editor, how to make your
projects popular on Scratch.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:43.824
People do tutorials
about everything.

00:08:43.824 --> 00:08:45.990
So we found that just people
are using the community

00:08:45.990 --> 00:08:47.674
in so many different ways.

00:08:47.674 --> 00:08:49.590
So I think, just by
looking at these projects,

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:52.680
you can see what Ipzy is
taking away from participating

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:53.800
in the community.

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:57.150
And I think what we see is
Ipzy is really developing

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:58.367
as a creative thinker.

00:08:58.367 --> 00:09:00.450
And we think that's more
important today than ever

00:09:00.450 --> 00:09:00.950
before.

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:03.960
For us, it's not just about
learning the coding skills,

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:06.510
although, clearly, if you
look at the scrolling back,

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:08.945
Ipzy's clearly doing
learning some coding skills.

00:09:08.945 --> 00:09:10.320
But for us, what's
most important

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:13.109
is that Ipzy's really
learning to think creatively.

00:09:13.109 --> 00:09:15.150
And I think that's more
important today than ever

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:15.730
before.

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:17.188
You know, we live
in a world that's

00:09:17.188 --> 00:09:20.370
changing so quickly that we
don't know exactly what skills

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:22.429
kids will need in the
future as they grow up,

00:09:22.429 --> 00:09:24.720
but we know they're going to
need to be able to come up

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:27.190
with creative solutions to
the unexpected things they

00:09:27.190 --> 00:09:27.840
confront.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:29.589
Because they will be
confronting all sorts

00:09:29.589 --> 00:09:31.990
of unexpected and
new situations.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:33.690
And we think that's
what's happening

00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:35.940
with young people like Ipzy.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:37.740
So to try to support
that development

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:40.260
of creative thinking,
we developed Scratch

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:43.230
with four guiding principles.

00:09:43.230 --> 00:09:46.170
We called them the four P's of
creative learning-- project,

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:47.767
passion, peers, and play.

00:09:47.767 --> 00:09:49.350
So with everything
we do, whether it's

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:51.840
developing Scratch,
or running a workshop,

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:53.790
or giving advice to
parents about what toys

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:55.320
to get for their
kids, we're always

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:58.110
guided by thinking about
these four P's, because it's

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:00.360
a good framework for thinking
about how you can really

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:02.754
help support creative thinking.

00:10:02.754 --> 00:10:04.170
So if you look at
Scratch, you can

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:08.160
see that it really is aligned
and guided by these four P's

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:09.700
of creative learning.

00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:10.860
The first one-- projects.

00:10:10.860 --> 00:10:13.320
Well, you saw Ipzy was just
constantly making projects,

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:16.020
and the Scratch website
is based on projects.

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:18.570
It's the core unit of
sharing on Scratch.

00:10:18.570 --> 00:10:21.054
There's 30 million projects
that kids have shared.

00:10:21.054 --> 00:10:22.470
Now, it might seem
obvious, if you

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:24.220
look at Scratch, you
say, well, of course,

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:25.600
they're working on projects.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:28.270
But that's not the way
most kids learn to code.

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:29.920
Go to most coding
websites and kids

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:32.710
are given a puzzle or
a problem to solve.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:33.880
They get the answer.

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:36.550
And then they're moved on
to a next puzzle or problem.

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:38.230
And again, when I
was 10 years old,

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:39.563
I would have enjoyed doing that.

00:10:39.563 --> 00:10:40.810
A lot of kids enjoy doing it.

00:10:40.810 --> 00:10:42.700
And you can learn some
computational concepts

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:43.450
that way.

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:45.350
There's nothing wrong with that.

00:10:45.350 --> 00:10:47.824
But if you really want to
develop as a creative thinker,

00:10:47.824 --> 00:10:49.240
it's not just a
matter of learning

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:52.410
how to solve a certain puzzle,
but being able to do a project.

00:10:52.410 --> 00:10:55.570
And with a project, I mean,
to start with your own idea,

00:10:55.570 --> 00:10:58.660
to develop some prototype
with it, to show it to others,

00:10:58.660 --> 00:11:02.020
to experiment with it, to get
feedback, to keep revising it,

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:04.752
to have a way of expressing
your ideas to the world.

00:11:04.752 --> 00:11:06.460
So with a project,
kids, they aren't just

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:09.549
developing their thinking, but
also developing their voice,

00:11:09.549 --> 00:11:11.590
coming up with an idea
and expressing their ideas

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:12.710
to the world.

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:15.400
So we really try to see Scratch
as it's like a type of writing.

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:17.050
The same way when
you learn to write,

00:11:17.050 --> 00:11:18.940
it's not just to get
tasks done, but it's

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:20.260
a way of expressing your ideas.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:24.130
We see Scratch the same way,
as kids work on projects.

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:27.040
And this second P of
passion, I think we all

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:30.820
know that we're all willing
to work longer and harder

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.270
and persist in the
face of challenges,

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:37.010
where we're working on something
we really care deeply about.

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:38.950
So for us, it's so
important to give kids

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:42.320
the opportunity to work on
things they really care about.

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:43.870
So as we were
developing Scratch,

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:46.453
we wanted to make sure that you
could do many different things

00:11:46.453 --> 00:11:46.960
with it.

00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:47.950
Because we know
that different kids

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:50.212
have different interests
and different passions,

00:11:50.212 --> 00:11:51.670
and we wanted to
make sure to align

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:53.440
with the interests of
all different kids.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:54.940
I mean, some people
suggested, well,

00:11:54.940 --> 00:11:57.640
why don't you do it so all
you do is to make games?

00:11:57.640 --> 00:11:58.450
Kids like games.

00:11:58.450 --> 00:12:00.700
And it's true, a lot
of kids like games.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:02.320
But about kids who
don't like games?

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.150
Then they wouldn't
be interested in it.

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:06.233
We wanted to make sure
that kids could make games,

00:12:06.233 --> 00:12:09.040
but they can also make
animations and simulations

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.280
and interactive stories.

00:12:10.280 --> 00:12:12.280
Because different kids
have different interests,

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:14.080
we wanted to let all
kids build on things

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:16.040
they really want to do.

00:12:16.040 --> 00:12:20.110
And you can see that in Ipzy's
case, where Ipzy was building

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:22.750
upon their interest in
drawing, and used that as a way

00:12:22.750 --> 00:12:24.760
to get into coding.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.840
With peers, we saw
from the beginning

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:30.400
that we really wanted to make
sure that learning to code

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.930
was a social experience,
that too often,

00:12:32.930 --> 00:12:34.420
when people think
of coding, they

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:37.270
think of the individual
sitting by themselves

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:38.380
looking at the screen.

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:40.990
And of course, you spend some
time doing that and, you know,

00:12:40.990 --> 00:12:43.600
sometimes that's an important
part of the process.

00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:45.100
But we know that
a lot of learning

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:48.050
happens in collaboration
with others.

00:12:48.050 --> 00:12:51.160
So when we launched Scratch, we
launched the online community

00:12:51.160 --> 00:12:55.240
at the same time, integrated
with the programming language.

00:12:55.240 --> 00:12:56.887
And to us, that was
really important.

00:12:56.887 --> 00:12:58.720
And a lot of people,
they weren't quite sure

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:00.137
what we were doing,
because why do

00:13:00.137 --> 00:13:02.386
you have to have an online
computer with a programming

00:13:02.386 --> 00:13:02.905
language?

00:13:02.905 --> 00:13:07.060
But for us, the online community
both served as a source of--

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:10.270
it was a way to have an
audience for what you'd created.

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:11.710
Because when you
create something,

00:13:11.710 --> 00:13:13.626
you want to be able to
share ideas with others

00:13:13.626 --> 00:13:16.550
and get feedback, because we
saw Ipzy getting feedback.

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:19.010
It also serves as a
source of inspiration.

00:13:19.010 --> 00:13:20.710
You can look at the
online community,

00:13:20.710 --> 00:13:24.130
and you see, again, millions of
projects that gives you ideas

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:26.090
of what you want to create.

00:13:26.090 --> 00:13:28.180
So we wanted to have
a way that would have

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:29.450
kids connect with each other.

00:13:29.450 --> 00:13:30.910
They would learn
with and from one

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:33.550
another, both to get feedback
and inspiration from one

00:13:33.550 --> 00:13:34.760
another.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.230
And then, finally, play, and
I sometimes call play the most

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:40.196
misunderstood of the P's.

00:13:40.196 --> 00:13:42.070
Because people here play
and they just think,

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:44.190
oh, it's about laughing
and having fun.

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:46.794
And there's nothing wrong
with laughing and having fun.

00:13:46.794 --> 00:13:48.460
But we think of play
in a different way.

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:52.000
We see it almost as an attitude,
or an approach, to the things

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:52.770
you're doing.

00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:54.460
When you have a
playful approach,

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:57.190
it means you're willing to
take risks, to try new things,

00:13:57.190 --> 00:14:00.310
to test the boundaries,
to experiment.

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:02.450
And we wanted to make
sure that was possible.

00:14:02.450 --> 00:14:05.830
So we've really set up Scratch
so it's easy to put things

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:07.030
together, take them apart.

00:14:07.030 --> 00:14:09.309
You can make your
programs sort of

00:14:09.309 --> 00:14:10.600
like building with LEGO bricks.

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:12.970
LEGO bricks are so tinkerable,
and you can play with them,

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:15.053
try new things, take it
apart, try something else,

00:14:15.053 --> 00:14:16.252
continually iterate.

00:14:16.252 --> 00:14:18.710
And we wanted to make Scratch
really easy to iterate so you

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:20.215
could keep experimenting.

00:14:20.215 --> 00:14:22.090
So that's what we did,
and tried to make it--

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:23.830
and we also, in
moderating the committee,

00:14:23.830 --> 00:14:26.980
to make sure the community
is a type of place

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:28.960
where you feel safe
experimenting and trying

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:30.070
new things.

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:33.800
So these four P's have guided
the things that we're doing.

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:35.440
And from this, I
think this really

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:39.760
underlies why Scratch has been
growing over the last 10 years.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:43.150
And it really has grown beyond
what we would have imagined.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:47.140
So last year, there were
200 million unique visitors

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:47.857
to Scratch.

00:14:47.857 --> 00:14:49.690
Now, not all of them
were creating projects.

00:14:49.690 --> 00:14:52.990
About 10%, about 20 million
people created projects.

00:14:52.990 --> 00:14:54.830
But people just
visiting and trying out

00:14:54.830 --> 00:14:56.890
Scratch and its things,
there's about 200 million

00:14:56.890 --> 00:14:58.540
unique visitors.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:00.480
You know, every
country in the world.

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:02.230
From the beginning,
we wanted to translate

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:03.730
to many different
languages, so it's

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:06.800
easy to make the blocks switch
to whatever language you want.

00:15:06.800 --> 00:15:09.140
And even if you see
someone else's project--

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:12.210
a project that was
done in New York--

00:15:12.210 --> 00:15:15.260
a child in Tokyo could look
at it and switch the blocks

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:19.060
to Japanese, make a change to
it, and a child in Buenos Aires

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:21.190
could then change the
blocks to Spanish.

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:23.860
So it facilitates collaboration
by everyone changing it

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:25.320
to their own language.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:28.600
45% female, 100%--
everything is free.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:31.160
The software is free,
the community is free.

00:15:31.160 --> 00:15:32.650
It's also open source.

00:15:32.650 --> 00:15:34.330
So we've really
tried to build it

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:37.050
where all of that development
is done in an open source way.

00:15:37.050 --> 00:15:38.630
And we have people helping out.

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:39.921
We've been really appreciative.

00:15:39.921 --> 00:15:41.765
A bunch of people of
Google have helped out.

00:15:41.765 --> 00:15:43.890
We did an initiative last
year through Google Serve

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:44.590
and people helped out.

00:15:44.590 --> 00:15:46.150
We hope, as we
continue to develop,

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:48.130
we'll have others
helping us out.

00:15:48.130 --> 00:15:50.650
And every day, there's
150,000 new projects

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:54.130
that kids are creating
in the Scratch community.

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:55.270
Who's creating them?

00:15:55.270 --> 00:15:57.336
This is a histogram of
the ages that people

00:15:57.336 --> 00:15:58.210
joined the community.

00:15:58.210 --> 00:16:00.070
The peak is at age 12.

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:02.530
And this pretty much hits
what we had aimed for.

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:05.530
When we developed Scratch,
we aimed at age 8 to 16,

00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:09.670
and that's roughly where
the bulk of the people are.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:11.680
After Scratch came out,
we did another version

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:16.444
called ScratchJr, which is for
ages 5 to 7 at the lower end.

00:16:16.444 --> 00:16:17.860
One thing that
took us by surprise

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:20.800
is there's more use at the
higher end than we imagined.

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:22.897
Because even though we
designed it for 8 to 16,

00:16:22.897 --> 00:16:25.480
it's getting used in a growing
number of introductory computer

00:16:25.480 --> 00:16:29.450
science courses at universities,
sometimes for a whole semester,

00:16:29.450 --> 00:16:31.300
sometimes just to get started.

00:16:31.300 --> 00:16:34.330
Like, at Harvard, they
use it as the first week

00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:36.930
of the introductory computer
science course there--

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:38.350
CS50.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.180
And they found that,
when they shifted over

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:41.950
to doing Scratch
in the beginning,

00:16:41.950 --> 00:16:43.990
the number of people
dropping the course

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:46.840
went down dramatically,
especially among women.

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:49.510
They used to have huge
dropout rates of women.

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:51.850
And at least, they speculate
that, with Scratch, people

00:16:51.850 --> 00:16:54.082
were able to have
success very quickly,

00:16:54.082 --> 00:16:55.540
and get a sense of
what's possible,

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:57.666
and what type of things
they might do with Scratch.

00:16:57.666 --> 00:16:59.123
And then, after
it, in that course,

00:16:59.123 --> 00:17:00.910
they do shift to other
things, but Scratch

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:04.285
serves as a foundation for
getting people started.

00:17:04.285 --> 00:17:06.910
Within the use of Scratch,
when it started 10 years ago,

00:17:06.910 --> 00:17:10.619
a lot of it was being used in
homes and after school centers.

00:17:10.619 --> 00:17:12.950
Right now, the fastest
growth is in schools.

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:14.380
There's a lot of--

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:17.050
you know, and that's partly
it's a cultural phenomenon

00:17:17.050 --> 00:17:19.480
that more schools are getting
interested in introducing

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:20.170
coding.

00:17:20.170 --> 00:17:22.540
So Scratch is being used
in many different schools.

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:26.020
Here in New York, it's one of
the languages that's really

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:28.810
being used, especially
in elementary schools,

00:17:28.810 --> 00:17:30.670
with the different
efforts and CS4--

00:17:30.670 --> 00:17:33.642
all efforts-- really
supporting the use of Scratch

00:17:33.642 --> 00:17:34.600
going out into schools.

00:17:34.600 --> 00:17:35.890
I wanted to give you
some sense of how

00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:37.614
it's being used in
schools, so I'll

00:17:37.614 --> 00:17:39.280
show a few examples
of things that we've

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:41.150
seen in different schools.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:42.910
The first one is from India.

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:46.550
This one is from Bangalore,
where this was a--

00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:48.430
I think it was a 13-year-old.

00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:50.980
It was in the science class,
where they were studying

00:17:50.980 --> 00:17:52.750
the layers of the earth.

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:56.164
So as their final project, they
were making a Scratch project

00:17:56.164 --> 00:17:58.330
about what they learned,
to share what they learned,

00:17:58.330 --> 00:17:59.620
about the layers of the earth.

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:01.840
So the teacher explained
to us that this

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:05.360
dude-- he's speaking his
native language of Kannada,

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:07.610
and he's explaining the
different layers of the earth.

00:18:07.610 --> 00:18:09.507
And what he was
really excited about

00:18:09.507 --> 00:18:11.715
was the fact that things
are moving inside the earth.

00:18:11.715 --> 00:18:13.030
So he's explaining
things are moving.

00:18:13.030 --> 00:18:15.280
And you can see, he gets
down to the water table where

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:19.570
things are moving and puts in
sound effects for the water

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:20.445
table.

00:18:20.445 --> 00:18:23.780
So it's, again,
a way of sharing.

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:25.780
So this was a case where
Scratch was actually

00:18:25.780 --> 00:18:28.360
introduced at school and
everyone was using it.

00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:31.480
Sometimes kids learn Scratch at
home, but bring it into school.

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:33.080
That's the next example.

00:18:33.080 --> 00:18:35.860
This is from a middle
school in the United States,

00:18:35.860 --> 00:18:39.550
where they were studying, in
a social studies class, Rapa

00:18:39.550 --> 00:18:41.140
Nui, or Easter Island.

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:43.210
The island's off
of South America.

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:45.795
And this student did something
sort of like "SimCity,"

00:18:45.795 --> 00:18:47.440
but Sim Rapa Nui.

00:18:47.440 --> 00:18:50.080
He had learned about the
economy and the culture.

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:52.280
And you know, fishing is
important to the economy,

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:54.070
so to survive there,
you have to cut down

00:18:54.070 --> 00:18:56.515
a branch to make a fishing
rod and go fishing.

00:18:56.515 --> 00:18:58.780
But if you take down
too many branches,

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:02.110
happiness goes down, because
there's a certain way that they

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:03.394
respect the environment.

00:19:03.394 --> 00:19:05.560
So it was a way for him to
show what he had learned,

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:08.750
but also to help other
people learn about Rapa Nui.

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:11.320
I'll show one more example
from an elementary school.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:13.180
And this is an elementary
school, where--

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:14.888
I really like these
examples-- where it's

00:19:14.888 --> 00:19:16.050
used across the curriculum.

00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:17.800
So this elementary
school teacher

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:20.020
introduces Scratch
and, in the same way

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:21.610
that if you learn
about-- you learn

00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:23.860
how to write, you use writing
in all of your classes,

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:26.260
whether it's history
or science, you

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:29.810
use your writing everywhere--
they used Scratch everywhere.

00:19:29.810 --> 00:19:32.110
This is an example
from a book report.

00:19:32.110 --> 00:19:34.490
When they read
"Charlotte's Web,"

00:19:34.490 --> 00:19:36.474
this was one of the
students book reports.

00:19:36.474 --> 00:19:38.140
And you can see,
they're using language.

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:40.547
They'd read the book and
they're writing about the book.

00:19:40.547 --> 00:19:42.880
But one thing that caught my
attention with this example

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:45.250
is notice how the
pig gets smaller

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:47.140
as it goes further away.

00:19:47.140 --> 00:19:49.630
So this was also using what
they learned in art class

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:52.660
about perspective, that to make
something look further away,

00:19:52.660 --> 00:19:53.970
you make it smaller.

00:19:53.970 --> 00:19:56.080
But then, if you
look at the code,

00:19:56.080 --> 00:19:58.600
in order to make it smaller,
what this student had to do

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:00.460
was multiply it by a fraction--

00:20:00.460 --> 00:20:02.710
multiply the size by a
fraction-- less than 1

00:20:02.710 --> 00:20:05.330
repeatedly to make it smaller
and smaller and smaller.

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:08.500
So he was learning mathematical
ideas while doing that.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:11.307
But again, using mathematical
ideas with a purpose.

00:20:11.307 --> 00:20:12.640
So there was a reason, you know?

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:14.680
They knew why they were
multiplying fractions.

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:17.080
Most kids, you're taught
multiplying fractions

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:19.347
and you think, why
am I learning this?

00:20:19.347 --> 00:20:21.430
But here, they were learning
multiplying fractions

00:20:21.430 --> 00:20:22.240
for a purpose.

00:20:22.240 --> 00:20:23.948
There was a reason
for doing it, and they

00:20:23.948 --> 00:20:25.780
could make good use of it here.

00:20:25.780 --> 00:20:28.830
Actually, right before this
talk, I was talking to Max.

00:20:28.830 --> 00:20:30.190
I was very happy he came.

00:20:30.190 --> 00:20:32.116
He was telling me about,
in his third grade,

00:20:32.116 --> 00:20:33.490
they were making
games where they

00:20:33.490 --> 00:20:36.640
had to show some things
about rocks and minerals,

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:38.169
so that other people
learn something

00:20:38.169 --> 00:20:40.210
they didn't know before
about rocks and minerals.

00:20:40.210 --> 00:20:42.670
So I think that's
another great example.

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:44.740
I think it was just
recently he was doing that.

00:20:44.740 --> 00:20:46.330
And that's a way
of sort of using

00:20:46.330 --> 00:20:48.700
Scratch as a way of
communicating and sharing

00:20:48.700 --> 00:20:49.520
with one another.

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:52.990
So I think we see more and
more of that happening.

00:20:52.990 --> 00:20:54.790
So in our collaboration
with Google,

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:57.010
we also are doing a lot
aiming at schools-- you know,

00:20:57.010 --> 00:20:59.019
with Google CS First program.

00:20:59.019 --> 00:21:01.060
It's an after school
initiative, but increasingly

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:02.200
being focused on in school.

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:04.360
So we see that as a
great collaboration.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:07.450
And we're really pleased
that, as CS First got started,

00:21:07.450 --> 00:21:10.140
they chose Scratch as the
primary programming language.

00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:12.681
So we've worked with them, and
it's been great to see the way

00:21:12.681 --> 00:21:15.559
that they have built all sorts
of resources around Scratch.

00:21:15.559 --> 00:21:18.100
So those types of collaborations
are really important for us,

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:19.640
because we have a
relatively small team.

00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:21.490
We have the language out
there, but the CS First team

00:21:21.490 --> 00:21:24.100
has done a great job of
creating all sorts of resources

00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:27.580
around it and supporting both
the mentors and facilitators

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:30.160
running these sessions,
and also developing

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:32.200
the materials for
kids to use as well.

00:21:32.200 --> 00:21:34.740
So we're really look
forward to doing that.

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:39.170
Let me give one more extended
example of one where--

00:21:39.170 --> 00:21:41.160
and we see this
happening a lot, where--

00:21:41.160 --> 00:21:43.920
of someone who starts to learn
Scratch in school, but then

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:46.320
continues doing things
outside of school.

00:21:46.320 --> 00:21:48.220
And that also makes
us really happy.

00:21:48.220 --> 00:21:50.680
Actually, I was at an event
in New York City-- actually,

00:21:50.680 --> 00:21:53.820
it was during CS Ed Week in
December, I was down here.

00:21:53.820 --> 00:21:57.630
And the CSforALL people had
an event that I went to.

00:21:57.630 --> 00:21:59.757
And there, I met a couple
of high school students.

00:21:59.757 --> 00:22:00.840
And I was talking to them.

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:02.640
And they weren't
using Scratch anymore.

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:04.660
They'd used it in elementary
and middle school.

00:22:04.660 --> 00:22:06.540
But what I really liked is
they said what they liked

00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:08.649
about Scratch was, they
said, it was the one thing

00:22:08.649 --> 00:22:11.190
they did at school they wanted
to continue to do on their own

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:12.570
after school.

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:14.740
And for us, I think
everything should be that way.

00:22:14.740 --> 00:22:16.531
So everything we develop,
we try to make it

00:22:16.531 --> 00:22:18.370
that kids would want
to do on their own.

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:20.911
And that was the case-- so this
is another member the scratch

00:22:20.911 --> 00:22:22.080
community.

00:22:22.080 --> 00:22:25.200
bubble103 is her user name.

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:26.800
She's from South Africa.

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:29.100
And she first learned
about Scratch in school,

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:30.780
where this is one
of the projects--

00:22:30.780 --> 00:22:34.330
if you go to the profile,
you can see the water cycle

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:39.480
and it shows how the water
from the lake or the ocean

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:41.910
goes up and makes a cloud,
and then it goes and it rains.

00:22:41.910 --> 00:22:43.750
So it's talking about
the water cycle.

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:44.730
But as she learned
that, she then

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:46.120
started making games on her own.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:48.510
There's a fabulous farming
game that she made.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:50.760
She made a presentation
about South Africa.

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:52.530
She was really proud
of South Africa.

00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:55.440
And she wanted to share
her pride with other people

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:56.580
in the community.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:23:00.210
And she also made
tutorials, like Ipzy did.

00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:01.634
And bubble103 had
used variables,

00:23:01.634 --> 00:23:04.050
and she was excited about what
she could do with variables

00:23:04.050 --> 00:23:06.130
and wanted to share
that with others.

00:23:06.130 --> 00:23:08.310
But the project that really
caught our attention,

00:23:08.310 --> 00:23:10.560
and a lot of people's
attention, was a project

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:12.900
that she worked on
called Colour Divide.

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:14.970
And this is a
collaborative project

00:23:14.970 --> 00:23:17.291
that she did with five
or six other scratchers.

00:23:17.291 --> 00:23:19.290
They were like in three
or four other countries.

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:24.000
So they started exchanging
ideas in the online community.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.570
And bubble103 had started this
role playing game with others,

00:23:27.570 --> 00:23:30.270
and then decided to make
a trailer for a movie

00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:32.790
that they wanted to make
about Colour Divide.

00:23:32.790 --> 00:23:36.270
So I'll show you now like a
one minute clip, this trailer

00:23:36.270 --> 00:23:36.900
that they did.

00:23:36.900 --> 00:23:39.000
And this is, again, five
different scratchers

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.260
working together to put
together the trailer for "Colour

00:23:43.260 --> 00:23:43.970
Divide."

