00:25:15.830 --> 00:25:17.900
And again, we see
this over and over.

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:19.750
A lot of the kids that
are using Scratch,

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.709
or oftentimes as they go
into their teen years,

00:25:21.709 --> 00:25:24.083
they're exploring things about
their own identity, things

00:25:24.083 --> 00:25:25.510
about the community around them.

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:27.009
So you see them
tackling issues that

00:25:27.009 --> 00:25:28.295
are deeply important to them.

00:25:28.295 --> 00:25:30.170
Of course, there's a
lot of things on Scratch

00:25:30.170 --> 00:25:31.822
that are just funny animations.

00:25:31.822 --> 00:25:33.530
But there also is an
opportunity for kids

00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:36.200
to really develop their
own ideas, to share

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:39.200
ideas with others, and
use it as a way to sort

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:40.910
through important ideas.

00:25:40.910 --> 00:25:44.180
And also, to sort through ways
of engaging with the design

00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:46.320
process and the
creative process.

00:25:46.320 --> 00:25:49.770
So bubble103 also said,
"Because of Scratch,

00:25:49.770 --> 00:25:51.610
I've become more confident
to try new things

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:52.980
and express myself--

00:25:52.980 --> 00:25:55.940
I'm more comfortable with taking
risks and making mistakes.

00:25:55.940 --> 00:25:57.320
Now, when something
goes wrong, I

00:25:57.320 --> 00:25:59.869
