to learn something new."

00:25:59.869 --> 00:26:02.160
And again, that's what we
were hoping for with Scratch.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:04.640
When I talked about the
importance of play, in my mind,

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:07.400
there's a playful approach,
a willingness to take risks,

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:09.700
a willingness to
have things go wrong,

00:26:09.700 --> 00:26:13.730
and then an ability to try to
iterate and to debug things

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:15.834
when things go wrong,
and to try new things.

00:26:15.834 --> 00:26:18.000
And that's exactly what she
was getting out of this.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.440
So we're really happy when we
hear scratchers talk this way.

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:23.870
And bubble103 also talked
about the importance

00:26:23.870 --> 00:26:25.690
of the online community for her.

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:27.440
She said, "I've been
constantly blown away

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:30.350
by the kind of support and
collaboration and sharing

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:31.890
that happens in the community.

00:26:31.890 --> 00:26:34.181
That's one of the main things
that keeps me coming back

00:26:34.181 --> 00:26:35.820
to Scratch every day."

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:38.360
And we see that over and
over, that, for a lot of kids,

00:26:38.360 --> 00:26:40.850
they come to Scratch
to create a project.

00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:42.345
They stay for the community.

00:26:42.345 --> 00:26:43.970
They connect with
other people, the way

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:45.095
they share with each other.

00:26:45.095 --> 00:26:49.370
In this case, collaborating
with others on projects,

00:26:49.370 --> 00:26:52.650
interacting and getting
inspired by others.

00:26:52.650 --> 00:26:55.340
And I think it's not an accident
that this example happens

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:58.010
to come from a young
woman in the community.

00:26:58.010 --> 00:27:00.652
Just last night-- this
is my freshest data--

00:27:00.652 --> 00:27:03.110
just last night, one of the
graduate students in our group,

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:05.720
Shruti Dhariwal,
was showing some

00:27:05.720 --> 00:27:08.990
of the last data she was
looking at about some gender

00:27:08.990 --> 00:27:10.400
differences on Scratch.

00:27:10.400 --> 00:27:15.500
As I mentioned, it's about 45%
female, the Scratch population.

00:27:15.500 --> 00:27:18.020
One thing we'd already
seen was that, if you

00:27:18.020 --> 00:27:20.840
look at the number of
projects that people create,

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:23.660
the boys and girls
on Scratch each

00:27:23.660 --> 00:27:26.050
create roughly the same
number of projects.

00:27:26.050 --> 00:27:29.120
But Shruti was just looking at
the data and saw the following,

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:31.010
as far as on the
social side of Scratch,

00:27:31.010 --> 00:27:33.429
where if you like a project,
you can give it a love.

00:27:33.429 --> 00:27:35.220
And if you look on the
left hand side here,

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:39.320
you see that the female
participants on Scratch

00:27:39.320 --> 00:27:40.520
are much more likely--

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:43.320
they give 50% more
loves than others.

00:27:43.320 --> 00:27:46.580
So on average, each female
participant gives 12 loves.

00:27:46.580 --> 00:27:48.500
Only 8 for male participants.

00:27:48.500 --> 00:27:51.050
As far as giving comments
on other projects,

00:27:51.050 --> 00:27:53.630
female participants,
28; male, 16--

00:27:53.630 --> 00:27:55.430
almost twice.

00:27:55.430 --> 00:27:57.860
And for me, I found
this really striking

00:27:57.860 --> 00:28:01.085
because we'd already seen,
in looking at the community,

00:28:01.085 --> 00:28:03.320
that getting social
feedback on the community

00:28:03.320 --> 00:28:05.060
is the most
important determinant

00:28:05.060 --> 00:28:07.460
about whether someone
stays on Scratch.

00:28:07.460 --> 00:28:10.340
So when someone puts up
a project on Scratch,

00:28:10.340 --> 00:28:13.130
how quickly they receive
some social feedback--

00:28:13.130 --> 00:28:14.540
a comment or a love--

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:17.960
has a huge influence on whether
they make a second project.

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:20.630
So the fact that the
young women on Scratch

00:28:20.630 --> 00:28:23.210
are doing much more
commenting and loving really

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:26.330
shows the important role
they're playing to help continue

00:28:26.330 --> 00:28:28.312
people working on Scratch.

00:28:28.312 --> 00:28:30.770
And it really shows how the
creative side and the community

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:32.570
side of Scratch really
are tightly linked

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:33.279
with one another.

00:28:33.279 --> 00:28:35.319
So this is something that
we continue to look at.

00:28:35.319 --> 00:28:37.850
And I think, right now, we're
sitting on top this huge trove

00:28:37.850 --> 00:28:41.370
of data, because there's 30
million projects on Scratch,

00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:42.836
and we've saved everything.

00:28:42.836 --> 00:28:44.210
So we're still
sorting through it

00:28:44.210 --> 00:28:46.520
to try to learn more
about the creative process

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:51.130
and the coding process, as we
sort through this on Scratch.

00:28:51.130 --> 00:28:53.500
I wanted to end by giving
some examples looking ahead,

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:56.040
about the next generation of
Scratch that we're working on.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:57.790
So we're now working
on a third generation

00:28:57.790 --> 00:29:03.070
of Scratch called Scratch 3.0
that will launch this August.

00:29:03.070 --> 00:29:06.430
The first generation of
Scratch that came out in 2007

00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:11.350
was a downloadable application
that you used locally.

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:13.840
And then, you could
share on the website,

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:14.980
where the community was.

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:16.330
If you saw something
in the community that

00:29:16.330 --> 00:29:19.000
looked interesting, you had
to download it to see the code

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:20.990
and play with the code.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:24.160
The second generation
of Scratch, in 2013,

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:25.900
was all in the browser.

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:28.360
So you could start
authoring in the browser.

00:29:28.360 --> 00:29:30.460
And that really led to a
real growth in Scratch.

00:29:30.460 --> 00:29:34.660
It really removed a
lot of the friction

00:29:34.660 --> 00:29:36.389
between creating and sharing.

00:29:36.389 --> 00:29:38.430
So you could sort of see
things in the community,

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:43.030
go inside right away,
right online see the code,

00:29:43.030 --> 00:29:45.197
manipulate the code,
try different things.

00:29:45.197 --> 00:29:46.780
So it really opened
up and really lead

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:50.390
to some of the recent
growth in Scratch.

00:29:50.390 --> 00:29:52.500
The third generation
we're coming out now,

00:29:52.500 --> 00:29:55.230
one of the motivations for
it is to make it much better

00:29:55.230 --> 00:29:56.670
suited for mobile.

00:29:56.670 --> 00:29:59.580
You know, back in
around 2010 or so,

00:29:59.580 --> 00:30:01.770
as we started working
on Scratch 2.0,

00:30:01.770 --> 00:30:03.270
we made the decision
to implement it

00:30:03.270 --> 00:30:06.985
in Flash, which, at the time,
seemed like a good decision.

00:30:06.985 --> 00:30:08.610
Right now, that is
not looking so good,

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:10.990
so we really need to be moving
into a new infrastructure.

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:13.800
So Scratch 3.0 will
be all HTML5-based.

00:30:13.800 --> 00:30:17.110
It will be much more
designed with mobile in mind.

00:30:17.110 --> 00:30:19.230
So that's one thing
that we wanted to do,

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:20.810
and we sort of need to do.

00:30:20.810 --> 00:30:22.440
But we also wanted
to make it much more

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:25.889
of a basic platform
that can be extended

00:30:25.889 --> 00:30:27.180
in all sorts of different ways.

00:30:27.180 --> 00:30:29.679
And this is something, again,
we've done a lot collaboration

00:30:29.679 --> 00:30:30.630
with Google.

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:32.940
For the programming
language itself,

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:35.160
we've been working
with the Blockly team,

00:30:35.160 --> 00:30:37.740
and building on the
infrastructure of Blockly

00:30:37.740 --> 00:30:38.984
from here.

00:30:38.984 --> 00:30:40.650
But then, using some
of the design ideas

00:30:40.650 --> 00:30:43.025
we've had from Scratch, we've
had the great collaboration

00:30:43.025 --> 00:30:46.110
of working together on
the new set of blocks

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:48.540
that we were using for this.

00:30:48.540 --> 00:30:50.580
And these blocks,
again, are open source,

00:30:50.580 --> 00:30:52.170
as Blockly has been.

00:30:52.170 --> 00:30:55.840
So in addition to using these
blocks in our Scratch 3.0,

00:30:55.840 --> 00:30:58.490
we want to have this
as a standard grammar

00:30:58.490 --> 00:31:00.300
for a block-based
programming that anybody

00:31:00.300 --> 00:31:02.790
can embed in their
own apps or toys

00:31:02.790 --> 00:31:04.322
or whatever products they have.

00:31:04.322 --> 00:31:06.780
So we're trying to make this
sort of a standard programming

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:08.310
grammar for everybody.

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.830
But then, we'll also use
it inside our own version

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:13.999
of Scratch 3.0.

00:31:13.999 --> 00:31:16.290
Another way in which we're
extending Scratch and making

00:31:16.290 --> 00:31:20.670
it more modular is making it
much easier to extend Scratch.

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:23.490
So in addition to the core
capabilities of Scratch,

00:31:23.490 --> 00:31:25.680
we're having a whole, what
we call, the extension

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.850
mechanism to make
it easy for people

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:30.120
to add new Scratch blocks.

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:34.380
So of course, we want to have it
so that we can extend Scratch,

00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:36.780
but we also want to let
everybody else extend Scratch

00:31:36.780 --> 00:31:37.740
as well.

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:39.780
So now, this is
not necessarily--

00:31:39.780 --> 00:31:40.921
most kids won't do this.

00:31:40.921 --> 00:31:41.670
But this is more--

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:44.610
developers can add their
own Scratch blocks.

00:31:44.610 --> 00:31:47.070
And there's a way down
here, just in the interface,

00:31:47.070 --> 00:31:49.080
if you just want to
add an extension,

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:51.794
you can go down to the bottom
left corner, add an extension.

00:31:51.794 --> 00:31:53.710
Let me give you some
examples of how to do it.

