[BOUNCY SOUNDS]

00:35:17.324 --> 00:35:18.990
And you know, I think
a big part of what

00:35:18.990 --> 00:35:22.650
we end up doing in our group--

00:35:22.650 --> 00:35:25.830
if we see inside,
we can take a look.

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:30.710
And this is the key block.

00:35:30.710 --> 00:35:32.400
You have very few new blocks.

00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:35.760
This one just says, if there's
video motion on this sprite,

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:38.710
and it's grabbed by the
threshold, then do something.

00:35:38.710 --> 00:35:41.280
So obviously, there's a
huge amount of information

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:42.390
coming from the camera.

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:43.890
I think a big thing
about what we do

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.140
is how can we take
all that information,

00:35:46.140 --> 00:35:48.000
put it into the right
building blocks,

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.580
to let kids use it
in a meaningful way.

00:35:50.580 --> 00:35:52.830
So we just did it, so you
see how much motion there

00:35:52.830 --> 00:35:54.260
is on your sprite.

00:35:54.260 --> 00:35:57.090
In this case, if the
minifig is falling,

00:35:57.090 --> 00:35:58.740
it sees motion in
the background,

00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:00.840
it then jumps upwards.

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:03.090
We also have it that you can
see what direction it is.

00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:05.610
So you could also do it,
if I swat in one direction,

00:36:05.610 --> 00:36:07.500
it can move one way
or the other way.

00:36:07.500 --> 00:36:10.140
But just a few simple
primitives is what we're doing.

00:36:10.140 --> 00:36:12.900
We're also, in 3.0, extending
this to do some things

00:36:12.900 --> 00:36:15.180
with object detection.

