00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:44.460
So basically, you can translate
a word to any language,

00:36:44.460 --> 00:36:46.470
or you could just have
it translate whatever

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:47.790
the web browser is set to.

00:36:47.790 --> 00:36:50.070
So I can make this, and
then it would translate

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:53.580
things to whatever the person
using the project, whatever

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:55.100
their browser is set to.

00:36:55.100 --> 00:36:57.310
But if I just set it to
a particular language,

00:36:57.310 --> 00:37:00.820
so I could just, say, to French.

00:37:00.820 --> 00:37:03.990
So if I translate French
hello, it says bonjour.

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:07.680
I can then put it inside a say
block to have the cat say--

00:37:10.279 --> 00:37:11.070
so normally-- oops.

00:37:14.718 --> 00:37:16.830
So there's the cat saying hello.

00:37:16.830 --> 00:37:20.660
But now, if I just
say, translate hello

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:23.970
to French for two seconds,
now the cat will say, bonjour.

00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:25.470
And if instead of
saying to French,

00:37:25.470 --> 00:37:27.600
I say, translate hello to
wherever the browser is

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:30.090
set to, well, then, the cat
will talk in whatever language

00:37:30.090 --> 00:37:31.607
the browser is set to.

00:37:31.607 --> 00:37:32.940
So these are things we're doing.

00:37:32.940 --> 00:37:34.440
So again, this is
a great thing that

00:37:34.440 --> 00:37:36.050
came out of the collaboration.

00:37:36.050 --> 00:37:39.282
I'll show one more
sort of a fake example,

00:37:39.282 --> 00:37:41.490
because this isn't actually
running in the prototype.

00:37:41.490 --> 00:37:46.630
So it's a little bit of
a trick, just to show you

00:37:46.630 --> 00:37:50.210
what we're aiming for.

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:54.140
Again, we're working with Google
on speech recognition blocks.

00:37:54.140 --> 00:37:56.390
We know that obviously
communicating with speech

00:37:56.390 --> 00:37:59.300
is something that kids are
interacting with all the time

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:00.090
now.

00:38:00.090 --> 00:38:01.465
But for us, it's
really important

00:38:01.465 --> 00:38:04.050
that kids don't just spend
their time feeling it's magical,

00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:07.044
talking to something and
then it talks back to you.

00:38:07.044 --> 00:38:09.460
We want kids to feel that they
can create things this way.

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:11.668
So we want kids to be able
to create their own speech

00:38:11.668 --> 00:38:12.560
interfaces.

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:15.620
So we're having some new blocks
on the speech synthesis side,

00:38:15.620 --> 00:38:18.230
where you'll actually
say the words out

00:38:18.230 --> 00:38:20.030
loud with this
synthesized voice,

00:38:20.030 --> 00:38:22.590
but also do some
speech recognition.

00:38:22.590 --> 00:38:25.580
So like here's one where, if you
see the key part here, it says,

00:38:25.580 --> 00:38:28.670
when I hear what time is
it, it will then speak,

00:38:28.670 --> 00:38:30.380
it's party time.

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:32.150
And then, it'll play
a certain sound.

00:38:32.150 --> 00:38:33.496
So I say, what time is it?

00:38:33.496 --> 00:38:35.537
SYNTHESIZED VOICE (ON
COMPUTER): It's party time.

00:38:35.537 --> 00:38:37.922
[PARTY MUSIC PLAYING]

00:38:43.494 --> 00:38:45.160
MITCHEL RESNICK: So
again, our real hope

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:48.520
is that it will let kids
create their own type of speech

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:51.289
interfaces and conversational
interfaces with these blocks.

00:38:51.289 --> 00:38:53.080
And again, we're still
trying to figure out

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:54.370
the exact right building blocks.

00:38:54.370 --> 00:38:56.203
Because I think the key
thing is making sure

00:38:56.203 --> 00:39:00.160
that we preserve what's
the core power of it,

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:02.944
but make it simple enough
and versatile enough

00:39:02.944 --> 00:39:04.610
that kids are going
to be able to use it

00:39:04.610 --> 00:39:07.030
in many different ways.

00:39:07.030 --> 00:39:10.180
So just to wrap up, you
know, we see lots of ways

00:39:10.180 --> 00:39:13.840
that Scratch is
going to continue

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:15.610
to get out to the world.

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:20.200
And for us, we do want to see
it is a new type of fluency.

00:39:20.200 --> 00:39:22.720
It's something that, when
we teach kids to write,

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:25.370
it's not just so that they
can use writing in their jobs,

00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:27.460
although people do use
writing in their jobs,

00:39:27.460 --> 00:39:30.110
but so that they can express
their ideas to the world.

00:39:30.110 --> 00:39:31.600
And we see Scratch the same way.

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:33.370
We want to let all
kids grow up feeling

00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:36.280
they can use the powerful
technology of their times

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:38.380
in a way that they can
express their voice,

00:39:38.380 --> 00:39:40.670
express their
ideas, to the world.

00:39:40.670 --> 00:39:43.330
And to do that, we want to
keep on that focus of projects,

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:44.372
passion, peers, and play.

00:39:44.372 --> 00:39:46.538
Because there's always going
to be new technologies,

00:39:46.538 --> 00:39:48.820
whether it's object
recognition, speech recognition,

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:49.750
speech synthesis.

00:39:49.750 --> 00:39:51.700
We want to keep integrating
new technologies,

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:54.130
but always in this
framework of providing kids

00:39:54.130 --> 00:39:55.660
with creative
learning experiences

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:58.150
and leaving them in control,
so that it's not they're just

00:39:58.150 --> 00:40:00.629
interacting with things, but
things where they can do it.

00:40:00.629 --> 00:40:02.920
Because I think that's going
to be the key to help kids

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:05.740
grow up to become full
and active contributors

00:40:05.740 --> 00:40:07.630
in tomorrow's society.

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:09.130
If you want to read
more about this,

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:13.500
I did just finish a book that is
called "Lifelong Kindergarten."

00:40:13.500 --> 00:40:15.159
We use the metaphor
of kindergarten,

00:40:15.159 --> 00:40:17.200
because I've been really
inspired by the way kids

00:40:17.200 --> 00:40:18.340
learn in kindergarten.

00:40:18.340 --> 00:40:21.190
The idea of the four P's
came from observing kids

00:40:21.190 --> 00:40:21.910
in kindergarten.

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:24.530
If you think of the
classic kindergarten,

00:40:24.530 --> 00:40:28.330
that kids are building towers
with blocks, making pictures

00:40:28.330 --> 00:40:30.049
with finger paints and crayons.

00:40:30.049 --> 00:40:31.840
In the process, they
learn important ideas.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:34.342
They build a tower, they learn
about structure stability.

00:40:34.342 --> 00:40:35.800
But even more
important, they learn

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:37.550
about the creative process.

00:40:37.550 --> 00:40:39.550
You know, they learn how
to put things together,

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:42.460
to experiment, to iterate.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:44.560
Too often, when they
leave kindergarten,

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:46.900
they end up sitting in
desks, listening to lectures,

00:40:46.900 --> 00:40:47.967
filling out worksheets.

00:40:47.967 --> 00:40:50.050
And that doesn't provide
them with the opportunity

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:52.329
to continue to develop
as creative thinkers.

00:40:52.329 --> 00:40:54.370
So they really aren't
getting prepared for what's

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:56.290
needed in today's society.

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:59.620
And to make matters worse, you
know, a lot of kindergartens

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:03.130
today, you go in there and kids
are drilling on math flashcards

00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:05.080
and doing phonics worksheets.

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:07.364
Kindergarten is becoming
more like the rest of school.

00:41:07.364 --> 00:41:09.780
And what we want to do, and
what I talk about in the book,

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:12.010
is to make the rest of
school, the rest of life, more

00:41:12.010 --> 00:41:13.060
like kindergarten.

00:41:13.060 --> 00:41:15.190
And that really inspired
us with Scratch.

00:41:15.190 --> 00:41:17.992
So from kindergarten, we got the
four P's that inspired Scratch.

00:41:17.992 --> 00:41:20.200
So the book tells you more
about the underlying ideas

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:21.985
for Scratch, to do it.

