00:42:26.719 --> 00:42:28.510
but are a little
confusing, at least to me.

00:42:28.510 --> 00:42:29.426
MITCHEL RESNICK: Yeah.

00:42:29.426 --> 00:42:34.750
So here's-- I'll give a
little bit of history.

00:42:34.750 --> 00:42:37.620
So Scratch got
started around 2007.

00:42:37.620 --> 00:42:40.270
And there were some other
people, based on Scratch,

00:42:40.270 --> 00:42:42.660
that started working on other
blocks related languages.

00:42:42.660 --> 00:42:45.270
And in fact, some of the other
things that got done then

00:42:45.270 --> 00:42:46.060
inspired Blockly.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.950
Another MIT professor,
named Hal Abelson,

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:52.730
spent a sabbatical at Google,
worked with others at Google,

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:56.190
and started the Blockly project.

00:42:56.190 --> 00:42:58.730
Or at least he started
App Inventor, which

00:42:58.730 --> 00:43:00.350
was making use of Blockly.

00:43:00.350 --> 00:43:02.030
So it's sort of
using together some

00:43:02.030 --> 00:43:04.210
of these same block-based
programming ideas.

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:07.400
But Blockly was being developed
separately from Scratch.

00:43:07.400 --> 00:43:09.140
But it was in the same spirit.

00:43:09.140 --> 00:43:12.140
As we started working on Scratch
3.0, we decided to join forces,

00:43:12.140 --> 00:43:13.640
because we saw that
each of us could

00:43:13.640 --> 00:43:15.320
gain from working together.

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:20.030
We had lots of experience of
how to make these blocks really

00:43:20.030 --> 00:43:22.670
work well with kids, so we had
a lot more experience working

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:26.390
with kids, where the Blockly
group had a great experience,

00:43:26.390 --> 00:43:29.090
and great expertise, in
making a great infrastructure

00:43:29.090 --> 00:43:30.789
for these blocks-based
languages.

00:43:30.789 --> 00:43:32.330
So we saw what each
of us had to gain

00:43:32.330 --> 00:43:33.620
from working with one another.

00:43:33.620 --> 00:43:34.920
So we've joined forces.

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:38.420
So basically, our new
version of Scratch blocks

00:43:38.420 --> 00:43:40.174
is building on top of Blockly.

00:43:40.174 --> 00:43:42.590
So our Scratch that we're using
are now on top of Blockly.

00:43:42.590 --> 00:43:44.060
It's a fork off a Blockly.

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:45.740
Blockly continues
to be developed,

00:43:45.740 --> 00:43:48.170
and we're sort of
building on top of that

00:43:48.170 --> 00:43:52.370
and making it specialized
especially for kids.

00:43:52.370 --> 00:43:54.350
Code.org, which is a
separate organization,

00:43:54.350 --> 00:43:57.560
has a separate site, is
focused on getting kids engaged

00:43:57.560 --> 00:43:59.900
with coding and CS Education.

00:43:59.900 --> 00:44:02.834
They have used Blockly in
a lot of their activities.

00:44:02.834 --> 00:44:04.250
So they've put a
lot of activities

00:44:04.250 --> 00:44:08.500
online of their own, some
of which used Blockly.

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:12.110
So Blockly gets used
by many other sites.

00:44:12.110 --> 00:44:15.230
Code.org also features many
other types of activities

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:15.730
by others.

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:17.270
So our work with
Scratch sometimes

00:44:17.270 --> 00:44:19.730
will get featured on
the Code.org site.

00:44:19.730 --> 00:44:22.190
So Code.org is sort of
this general site that

00:44:22.190 --> 00:44:25.070
has their own activities,
some of them based on Blockly,

00:44:25.070 --> 00:44:27.590
but also they feature,
especially at CS Ed Week

00:44:27.590 --> 00:44:29.667
other coding activities.

00:44:29.667 --> 00:44:31.000
Hopefully, that gave some sense.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:31.833
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:34.289 --> 00:44:34.830
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:44:34.830 --> 00:44:36.132
Thanks a lot for being here.

00:44:36.132 --> 00:44:37.590
My previous job,
before I was here,

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:39.721
was as a K-12 math
and coding teacher.

00:44:39.721 --> 00:44:41.220
And I used Scratch
in the classroom,

00:44:41.220 --> 00:44:42.750
but this was right
around when 2.0 came out,

00:44:42.750 --> 00:44:45.000
before you had a lot of the
classroom management tools

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
that I think you've had
in the past few years.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.666
And I'm just curious, as Scratch
moves into a lot of classrooms,

00:44:49.666 --> 00:44:51.450
as you noted, with CS4
and other programs,

00:44:51.450 --> 00:44:52.590
I'm curious how you
feel about-- like,

00:44:52.590 --> 00:44:53.910
you mentioned the
projects on the one hand,

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:55.290
and sort of the flash
cards and the drilling

00:44:55.290 --> 00:44:56.700
on the other hand--
like, how do you

00:44:56.700 --> 00:44:58.200
feel about Scratch
being sort of molded

00:44:58.200 --> 00:45:00.420
to fit into a mandatory
classroom environment, where

00:45:00.420 --> 00:45:02.825
people are interested in
defined learning metrics,

00:45:02.825 --> 00:45:04.950
seeing progress, assessments,
and things like that?

00:45:04.950 --> 00:45:05.520
MITCHEL RESNICK: Yeah.

00:45:05.520 --> 00:45:06.340
That's a good question.

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:08.840
And I mean, I do think we want
to make sure that, as Scratch

00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:12.050
moves into schools, that what
we love most about Scratch

00:45:12.050 --> 00:45:13.600
doesn't get squeezed out of it.

00:45:13.600 --> 00:45:15.530
And I think there are
ways of doing that.

00:45:15.530 --> 00:45:18.429
But I think we are constantly
working on, and working

00:45:18.429 --> 00:45:20.970
with educators, to feel what
are the best ways of introducing

00:45:20.970 --> 00:45:23.610
Scratch into classrooms
and maintaining

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:25.050
the spirit of Scratch.

00:45:25.050 --> 00:45:27.134
One of my former
students, who's now

00:45:27.134 --> 00:45:29.550
a professor at Harvard Graduate
School of Education, Karen

00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:31.500
Brennan, has done a
great job of this.

00:45:31.500 --> 00:45:34.350
She's made a curriculum
called the Creative Computing

00:45:34.350 --> 00:45:35.490
Curriculum Guide.

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:37.950
It's based on Scratch,
but it is very--

00:45:37.950 --> 00:45:41.140
it's shown how to make use
of it in classroom settings.

00:45:41.140 --> 00:45:45.210
So that's one example of trying
to take this Scratch program

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:46.687
language, but
introduced in a way

00:45:46.687 --> 00:45:48.270
that we feel stays
true to the values,

00:45:48.270 --> 00:45:51.810
but still is aligned with
the needs of classrooms.

00:45:51.810 --> 00:45:52.740
So there are many--

00:45:52.740 --> 00:45:54.130
others work on that as well.

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.010
So I think Scratch,
and other languages,

00:45:56.010 --> 00:45:58.170
are getting introduced
in many different ways.

00:45:58.170 --> 00:46:00.780
Our hope is to try to
make sure that it gets out

00:46:00.780 --> 00:46:03.840
to the world in a way that
stays true to those values.

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:05.324
But there are tensions there.

00:46:05.324 --> 00:46:07.740
I think some of the tensions
come about because the things

00:46:07.740 --> 00:46:08.940
that we care about most--

00:46:08.940 --> 00:46:10.590
I talked earlier
about the importance

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:13.230
of helping kids learn
to think creatively--

00:46:13.230 --> 00:46:15.840
it's not easy to get a
quantitative measure of how

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:18.360
you've advanced in
your creative thinking.

00:46:18.360 --> 00:46:21.030
It's much easier to get
a quantitative measure

00:46:21.030 --> 00:46:24.529
of how often do you use
conditional statements.

00:46:24.529 --> 00:46:26.070
So you can look at
someone's projects

00:46:26.070 --> 00:46:27.736
and see they're using
conditionals more,

00:46:27.736 --> 00:46:29.910
and grade them based on that.

00:46:29.910 --> 00:46:33.020
We hope that that's not the way
kids end up being evaluated,

00:46:33.020 --> 00:46:34.770
because that'll sort
of distort, we think,

00:46:34.770 --> 00:46:36.140
what is going to
be most important.

00:46:36.140 --> 00:46:37.240
They'll be learning
something that way.

00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:39.370
It's not saying that
there's no value in that.

00:46:39.370 --> 00:46:41.910
But I think we want to make
sure that kids continue

00:46:41.910 --> 00:46:44.520
to have this learning, not
just the core computational

00:46:44.520 --> 00:46:47.190
concepts, but also
design strategies

00:46:47.190 --> 00:46:48.840
and creative ways of thinking.

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:51.690
So we're constantly
working with educators

00:46:51.690 --> 00:46:53.550
trying to feel the
best way of doing that.

00:46:53.550 --> 00:46:54.880
It's an ongoing process.

00:46:54.880 --> 00:46:57.789
I think a lot of people are
continuing to work on it.

00:46:57.789 --> 00:46:58.330
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:58.330 --> 00:47:02.200
I have a question about the
design of the Scratch language.

00:47:02.200 --> 00:47:04.300
I think, in a lot of
other languages, some

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:05.940
of those complicated
things that you

00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:10.120
were talking about, like playing
audio, might be part of an SDK,

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:12.790
or a standard
library, or something.

00:47:12.790 --> 00:47:15.820
Whereas, in Scratch,
maybe those are

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:17.590
more like keywords
or blocks that

00:47:17.590 --> 00:47:18.760
are built into the language.

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:20.860
So I was just wondering
what you thought about that?

00:47:20.860 --> 00:47:21.776
MITCHEL RESNICK: Yeah.

00:47:21.776 --> 00:47:23.680
Well, we wanted to--
as we started Scratch,

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:25.840
we wanted to have
a relatively-- we

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:27.580
wanted to make it
easy for everyone

00:47:27.580 --> 00:47:30.500
to have sort of of this
consistent collection that

00:47:30.500 --> 00:47:32.380
was going to be used.

00:47:32.380 --> 00:47:35.397
And we worried that there are
too many different things.

00:47:35.397 --> 00:47:37.480
If you have to go and
search for different things,

00:47:37.480 --> 00:47:38.860
it was going to make it
more challenging for people

00:47:38.860 --> 00:47:39.485
to get started.

00:47:39.485 --> 00:47:40.943
So we tried to
figure out what were

00:47:40.943 --> 00:47:43.030
the core things we felt
was most important,

00:47:43.030 --> 00:47:45.850
and there's 100 or so
core blocks in Scratch.

00:47:45.850 --> 00:47:47.809
And we tried to think,
what are the things that

00:47:47.809 --> 00:47:49.974
are going to be most important
for the way kids want

00:47:49.974 --> 00:47:51.040
to express themselves.

00:47:51.040 --> 00:47:53.590
Before we started
Scratch, Tammy had

00:47:53.590 --> 00:47:56.560
mentioned we had developed
these network of after school

00:47:56.560 --> 00:47:59.170
centers called Computer
Clubhouses for young people

00:47:59.170 --> 00:48:00.660
in low income communities.

00:48:00.660 --> 00:48:02.950
And we saw that kids
at these clubhouses,

00:48:02.950 --> 00:48:06.040
they wanted to create their own
interactive stories and games,

00:48:06.040 --> 00:48:08.002
and they loved
manipulating media.

00:48:08.002 --> 00:48:09.460
But there weren't
good tools to let

00:48:09.460 --> 00:48:11.460
them create their interactive
stories and games.

00:48:11.460 --> 00:48:13.240
So we definitely
had them in mind.

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:15.531
So we wanted to make sure
they were the right primitive

00:48:15.531 --> 00:48:19.000
building blocks to let you
manipulate sound, music,

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:20.740
images, you know, photos.

00:48:20.740 --> 00:48:23.519
Make it easy to bring in your
own and also to personalize it,

00:48:23.519 --> 00:48:25.810
to bring in your own voice,
to bring in your own songs,

00:48:25.810 --> 00:48:27.410
bring your own images.

00:48:27.410 --> 00:48:31.450
So we put a priority on that to
making our core set of things.

00:48:31.450 --> 00:48:34.000
And we found you could
go pretty far with that.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.520
As you can see now, we are
having these extensions.

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:39.010
We're trying to see how we
can keep with that core set,

00:48:39.010 --> 00:48:43.070
but still make it possible
to extend in different ways.

00:48:43.070 --> 00:48:46.720
There's still challenges
that we have to think about.

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:48.820
By having an online
community, that's

00:48:48.820 --> 00:48:50.720
one reason we wanted
to keep it consistent.

00:48:50.720 --> 00:48:52.720
So if you saw something
on the online community,

00:48:52.720 --> 00:48:55.354
it was clear that you had
all the tools to make it.

00:48:55.354 --> 00:48:57.520
So now, if you see something
on the online community

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:00.507
that's using the micro:bit, but
you don't have the micro:bit,

00:49:00.507 --> 00:49:01.340
what does that mean?

00:49:01.340 --> 00:49:02.140
Is it confusing?

00:49:02.140 --> 00:49:04.662
So we're trying to figure how
to keep the community done

00:49:04.662 --> 00:49:06.370
in a way that you
could filter out things

00:49:06.370 --> 00:49:07.830
that aren't relevant for you.

00:49:07.830 --> 00:49:10.330
So those are still things that
we're trying to work through.

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:16.480
AUDIENCE: You
mentioned that you've

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:19.090
worked a little bit
with LEGO and Scratch,

00:49:19.090 --> 00:49:23.680
and I was wondering
if you guys were

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:29.500
working on kind of bringing
Scratch to MINDSTORMS?

00:49:29.500 --> 00:49:33.160
And you know, if you've
thought about the differences

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:38.230
between LEGO's approach to
a programming environment,

00:49:38.230 --> 00:49:40.600
where it's all
image-based and you

00:49:40.600 --> 00:49:45.610
have blocks that are just
pictures, and your approach,

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:50.244
where you have blocks that have
words on them, or like that?

00:49:50.244 --> 00:49:51.160
MITCHEL RESNICK: Yeah.

00:49:51.160 --> 00:49:52.900
And there's also some
other differences

00:49:52.900 --> 00:49:57.190
in the program language
that comes with MINDSTORMS.

00:49:57.190 --> 00:50:00.080
It also uses some different
programming paradigms as well.

00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:02.777
It's just the
icons versus words.

00:50:02.777 --> 00:50:05.110
It sort of grew out of a
dataflow tradition, rather than

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:06.310
a controlled flow tradition.

00:50:06.310 --> 00:50:08.350
So there's some differences
in some of the ways

00:50:08.350 --> 00:50:11.150
that the languages
are structured.

00:50:11.150 --> 00:50:14.290
We continue work
closely with LEGO.

00:50:14.290 --> 00:50:16.600
LEGO's working on the next
generation of MINDSTORMS.

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:18.550
We're working closely
with them and trying

00:50:18.550 --> 00:50:21.220
to influence some of
the ways that they'll

00:50:21.220 --> 00:50:22.570
be doing this in the future.

00:50:22.570 --> 00:50:23.944
Obviously, we're
deeply committed

00:50:23.944 --> 00:50:25.720
to the Scratch approach.

00:50:25.720 --> 00:50:26.860
I do see that--

00:50:26.860 --> 00:50:31.060
we're committed to the Scratch
approach of the basic grammar,

00:50:31.060 --> 00:50:36.340
but for ScratchJr, we do use
icons, rather than words.

00:50:36.340 --> 00:50:38.950
And we think, in some
situations, partly based on age

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:41.050
or partly on other
factors, we think

00:50:41.050 --> 00:50:43.169
some of this using
the icons can be fine.

00:50:43.169 --> 00:50:44.710
If people haven't
seen, on ScratchJr,

00:50:44.710 --> 00:50:46.410
we use icons and
use it horizontally.

00:50:46.410 --> 00:50:48.700
You snap blocks
together horizontally,

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:49.804
as opposed to vertically.

00:50:49.804 --> 00:50:51.970
Because when you're using
icons, it makes more sense

00:50:51.970 --> 00:50:53.180
doing it that way.

00:50:53.180 --> 00:50:55.750
So we do see a place
for both word-based,

00:50:55.750 --> 00:51:00.100
text-based on the blocks,
and icons on the blocks,

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:01.700
based on different situations.

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:03.340
So we're working together.

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:05.169
In fact, on Scratch
3.0, we're building it

00:51:05.169 --> 00:51:06.710
all on the same
infrastructure, so it

00:51:06.710 --> 00:51:09.119
will be easier to switch
back and forth between them.

00:51:09.119 --> 00:51:11.410
And we think there's a role
for both, based on what age

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:14.779
you're aiming for, the
type of applications.

00:51:14.779 --> 00:51:16.070
AUDIENCE: Can I just follow up?

00:51:16.070 --> 00:51:21.379
Do you have an idea of what
that age switchover is between--

00:51:21.379 --> 00:51:22.295
MITCHEL RESNICK: Yeah.

00:51:22.295 --> 00:51:26.270
Well, what we chose for--
like, ScratchJr, we say 5 to 7,

00:51:26.270 --> 00:51:27.980
Scratch is 8 and up.

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:29.930
But it's not that
they're hard boundaries.

00:51:29.930 --> 00:51:31.310
We're also still exploring.

00:51:31.310 --> 00:51:33.890
I think, on different devices,
as we do more things with

00:51:33.890 --> 00:51:37.430
coding on mobile phones, we
think there might be some

00:51:37.430 --> 00:51:39.740
advantage-- if you're doing
small programs on phones--

00:51:39.740 --> 00:51:41.617
there might be some
advantages for all ages,

00:51:41.617 --> 00:51:43.700
starting with icon-based
blocks, where you're just

00:51:43.700 --> 00:51:45.290
doing small programs.

00:51:45.290 --> 00:51:48.840
If you're doing longer programs,
going to text makes more sense.

00:51:48.840 --> 00:51:50.949
So I think we're still
exploring some of the ways

00:51:50.949 --> 00:51:51.740
to go between them.

00:51:51.740 --> 00:51:53.240
It's not just age-based.

00:51:53.240 --> 00:51:54.591
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:51:54.591 --> 00:51:56.996
I just want to be
respectful of people's time.

00:51:56.996 --> 00:51:59.401
It's 1 o'clock now and I
think we're officially done.

00:51:59.401 --> 00:52:00.459
But Mitchel, you're--

00:52:00.459 --> 00:52:02.000
MITCHEL RESNICK:
Yeah, I'm happy to--

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:03.500
we could just maybe
call it an end,

00:52:03.500 --> 00:52:04.760
but I'm happy to stay
around and people can just

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:05.960
come up and talk informally.

00:52:05.960 --> 00:52:07.070
Maybe that makes sense?

00:52:07.070 --> 00:52:07.970
TAMMY STERN: Sure.

00:52:07.970 --> 00:52:08.270
MITCHEL RESNICK: OK.

00:52:08.270 --> 00:52:09.478
TAMMY STERN: Thank you again.

